The objective is to find abnormal behaviour when the pump was running normally.

The steps followed in the process are as follows:

  1. Exploratory Data Analysis. a) Number of datapoints b) DataType of column c) Duration of pump running dataset d) Distribution of values in each column(features) e) Proportion of null values in each cloumn

  2. Imputing null values using KNNImpute and Data scaling using StandardScaler (z scaling)

  3. Trained dataset on 3 different algorithms namely PCA + Mahalanobis Distance, KMeans, Autoencoder
  4. Aggregated the prediction from different algorithm to have less number False alarms.

As a result in the training set there are 8 anomalies and in test set there are 10 anomalies from days 23rd May, 26th May, 27th May, 7th June, 8th June and 9th June.

###### Cluster Profiling ############

def Cluster_Profiling(df, ClustureName):
    cluster_avg = df.groupby(ClustureName).mean()
    cluster_std = df.groupby(ClustureName).std()
    population_avg = df.mean()
    # Calculate relative importance of cluster's attribute value compared to population
    relative_imp = ((cluster_avg - population_avg)/ cluster_std).round(2)

    # Initialize a plot with a figure size of 8 by 2 inches 
    #plt.figure(figsize=(20, 12))
    #plt.title('Relative importance of attributes')

    # Plot the heatmap
    #sns.heatmap(data=relative_imp, annot=True, fmt='.2f', cmap='RdYlGn')
    #plt.show()
    return relative_imp




## distance of population mean with clusters
def cluster_diff(df, num_clusters, ClustureName):
    print("Number of points in each cluster\n{}\n\n".format(df.groupby(ClustureName).size()))
    print("Distance of population mean with clusters")
    population_avg = df.mean()
    pop_md_from_clusters = {}
    for i in range(num_clusters):
        ED = np.linalg.norm(population_avg-df[df[ClustureName] == i].mean())
        cos= 1-cosine_similarity(population_avg.values.reshape(1,-1), df[df[ClustureName] == i].mean().values.reshape(1,-1))[0][0]
        pop_md_from_clusters['C'+str(i)]= [ED.round(2), cos.round(2)]
        print("C{}: {}".format(i,pop_md_from_clusters['C'+str(i)]))
    return

Split Train test Data¶

I have splitted the dataset into 2 sets train (Data from the month May) and test (out of time, oot: Data from the month June). The different models are trained on the train set and the prediction is made on test set. I was not having the labels of the data and to avoid false alarms and to have stable prediction I have aggregated the prediction of all the three algorithms.

In [11]:
#Split data into train test
df_train = df[df.index.month == 5]
df_test = df[df.index.month == 6]

Impute missing values using records nearby. For this I have used KNNImputer which imputes the mean values of nearest neighbors found in the training set.

df_test_zscale = pd.DataFrame(scaler.transform(df_test), columns = df_test.columns, index = df_test.index)

The goal of the project is to detect abnormal behavior (anomalies) when the pump is running normally. In order to find this abnormality in pump running I have used three different unsupervised algorithm of Machnie Learning. This abnormal behaviour in pump running are outliers i.e., the corresponding reading from the pump will be different from usual reading of pump.

To proceed forward and to have a vague picture about the clusters and outliers present in data, I have projected the 47 dimensional data on to the 3 dimensional data using Principal Component Analysis (PCA) which projects the data into given n dimension using the eigen vectors corresponding to the highest n eigen values which inturn corresponds to direction of highest variation in data

I have used three algorithms in order to identify outliers namely PCA+Mahalanobis Distance, KMeans and Autoencoder

I will now one by one explain the the training procedure of the dfferent algorithms, the cluster they formed correponding outliers and the feature importance i.e., feature involved in cluster formation

The first algorithm I have used is PCA+Mahalanobis, second is KMeans and then Autoencoder.

Starting from PCA. I have projected thr data into lower dimension and then used Mahalanobis distance to find ditance between the individual data points (pump readings) and the average of all the readings, higher the distance of data points from average the maximum probability of data point is to be outlier.

According to the 3 sigma rule of finding outliers, 99.97% of points are closer to the average of the data i.e., withing the 3 standard deviation from mean, I have considered the points outside this limit as outlier and thus corresponding readings shows the abnormality in pump run.

The dimension to project data points are calculated by projecting cumulative sum of the variance explained by the dimensions.

KMeans Algorithm¶

I have used elbow method to find the Optium number of clusters in the dataset, plotted mean square error for different number clusters formed using KMeans.

In [23]:
############# KMeans ########################

clusters = range(1,15)

#Sum of squared distances of samples to their closest cluster center.
TSS = []
for i in clusters:
    kmeans = KMeans(n_clusters=i, random_state=0)
    kmeans.fit(df_train_zscale)
    TSS.append(kmeans.inertia_)
    
plt.plot(clusters,TSS, 'bx-')
plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 16, step=1))
plt.show()

Autoencoders¶

I have traind three autoencoders with different nodes and layers and in order to avoid overfitting has scaled the reconstruction error from each of the autoencoder and has aggregated the scaled reconstruction error. Plotted reconstruction error of training dataset, using hit and trial method selected the threshold value of outlier and detected the outliers in both training and test dataset.
